        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the magnetic field structure of the Keplerian disk in VLA1623 A at Band 7 with the minimum required observing time 3 hrs.  Band 7 is choosen in order to achieve the highest possible 
angular resolution, and the size of the disk (~3") is well within the 
1/3 of the primary beam.  Our previous SMA observations at 345GHz have shown a tentative detection toward the peak of VLA1623A at the level
of 1.3%+-0.3% with a noise level of 3.4 mJy/beam.
Our previous ALMA Cycle 0 observation at Band 6 has detected strong dust continuum flux toward A&amp;B. Assuming the spectral index is a constant in VLA1623A, we can estimate that the 10$\sigma$ contours for
our ALMA Cycle 0 observations will be 15 mJy/beam at Band 7.
With the minimun 3 hrs of observing time for polarization observations, we can achieve rms level of 0.03 mJy/beam.
Therefore, at the position of the 10$\sigma$ contours,
the lowest detectable polarization (3$\sigma$) is 0.09/15=0.6%,
which is higher than the leakage calibration accuracy (0.3%)
for extended source.  Therefore, we can reliably detect a polarization level higher than 0.6% in our target.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
