    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>The formation of disks is a crucial problem to star formation, since they are 
the central agents to transfer material from collapsing envelope to protostars
and to re-distribute the angular momentum.   
Some theoretical studies of magnetized cores suggest that 
it is very difficult to form a circumstellar disk in the earliest stages of 
the collapse due to the extremely effective magnetic braking effect,
while other reserches suggest that the misalignment between rotation and magnetic 
field axis can greatly reduce the effectiveness of magnetic braking and produce
relatively massive circumstellar disks in the protostellar phase.
We have discoverd a Kepleraian disk toward Class 0 source VLA1623A 
using our ALMA Cycle 0 data (Murillo, Lai, et al., 2013, A&amp;A, in press).
Among the three Class 0 Keplerian disks, VLA1623A is most likely to be 
the yongest. Therefore, probing the magnetic fields toward VLA1623A 
will provide us valuable information to distinguish the disk formation 
theories.







</prp:abstract>
